                <fr:route>/nt-0004/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Unique prime factorization">Unique prime factorization</fr:title>
                <fr:meta name="source">Dummit and Foote <fr:link href="/dummit-2004-abstract/" title="Abstract Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/dummit-2004-abstract/" display-uri="dummit-2004-abstract" type="local">Abstract Algebra</fr:link> Section 0.2</fr:meta>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>For any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>, we may write it as a product
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[n=p_{1}^{\alpha _{1}}(…)p_{k}^{\alpha _{k}}]]></fr:tex>
of distinct primes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p_{i}]]></fr:tex> and exponents <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _{i}\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>. Here "uniqueness" means if we have another factorization
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[n=q_{1}^{\beta _{1}}(…)q_{\ell }^{\beta _{\ell }},]]></fr:tex>
then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k=\ell ]]></fr:tex> and we have a bijection <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma \colon \{1,…,k\}\to \{1,…,\ell \}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p_{i}=q_{\sigma (i)}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _{i}=\beta _{\sigma (i)}]]></fr:tex>. In other words, the two factorizations differ only in the ordering of factors.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
