              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> be a fixed positive integer. Let us define the <fr:link href="/nst-0011/" title="Equivalence relation" uri="http://localhost:8000/nst-0011/" display-uri="nst-0011" type="local">Equivalence relation</fr:link> on the integers by
<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\sim  b\iff  n\mathrel {\bigm |}(b-a).]]></fr:tex>
This is reflexive (<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\sim  a]]></fr:tex> since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\mathrel {\bigm |}(a-a)]]></fr:tex>), symmetric (<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\sim  b\iff  n\mathrel {\bigm |}(b-a)\iff  n\mathrel {\bigm |}(a-b)\iff  b\sim  a]]></fr:tex>) and transitive.</html:p>
                <html:p>Then the quotient set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z} /\mathord {\sim }]]></fr:tex> is often denoted <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z} / n\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>. Moreover, there are well-defined operations <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[a]+[b]=[a+b]]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[a]\cdot [b]=[a\cdot  b]]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
